`has_gpu()` returns `true` for any non-CPU device in `gguf_devices`, including backends not explicitly recognized (e.g. `HIP`, `SYCL`, `OpenCL`). But `gguf_acceleration_labels` only checks `has_metal`, `has_cuda`, and `has_vulkan`, so for an unrecognised backend the labels list will be empty and `gguf_backend_description` will return `"Cross-platform, CPU inference"` — even though `sys.has_gpu()` is `true` and the device is listed in `ggufDevices` in the same JSON response.

The test `test_from_devices_handles_unknown_gpu_backends` already confirms the gap: a `ROCm` device yields `has_gpu()=true` but all three named flags are `false`. A frontend consuming the `system_info` response could therefore show `hasGpu: true` alongside `description: "CPU inference"`, which is contradictory.

A simple guard in `gguf_backend_description` (and `gguf_backend_note`) to fall back to a generic "GPU acceleration" label when `has_gpu()` is true but no named flags are set would close this discrepancy:

```rust
fn gguf_backend_description(sys: &local_gguf::system_info::SystemInfo) -> String {
    match gguf_acceleration_name(sys) {
        Some(acceleration) => format!("Cross-platform, {acceleration} GPU acceleration"),
        None if sys.has_gpu() => "Cross-platform, GPU acceleration".to_string(),
        None => "Cross-platform, CPU inference".to_string(),
    }
}
```
